The '''Breadalbane Hydro-Electric Scheme''' is a [[hydroelectric]] scheme in the [[Breadalbane, Scotland|Breadalbane]] area of [[Perthshire]], [[Scotland]]. It comprises seven power stations which generate power from the dams around [[Loch Lyon]], [[Loch Earn]] and [[Loch Tay]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Power from the Glens|url=http://sse.com/media/87078/powerfromtheglens.pdf|publisher=SSE|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref>

==History==
[[File:Finlarig Dam.png|thumb|The Lawers Dam is one of several providing Scotland with hydro-electric power.]]
[[File:Dalhonzie power station outfow, power station in the background - geograph.org.uk - 660108.jpg|thumb|Dalhonzie power station outfow, power station in the background]]
Construction began in 1951. The Lawers Dam section began generating in 1956.<ref name=canmore>{{cite web |url=http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/103355/details/lawers+dam/ |title=Lawers Dam |publisher=CANMORE |accessdate=2 May 2014}}</ref> The dam measures {{convert|344|m}} long and {{convert|42|m}} in height.<ref name=canmore/><ref name="CS80">{{cite book|last=Simeons|first=Charles|title=Hydro-Power: The Use of Water as an Alternative Source of Energy|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pE8JAwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA309&dq=Breadalbane%20hydro%201956&pg=PA309|year=1980|publisher=Pergamon Press|page=309}}</ref> Water descends a [[hydraulic head|vertical distance]] of {{convert|415|m}}, the highest drop of any scheme in Scotland.<ref name=gaz>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottish-places.info/features/featurefirst3841.html |title=Breadalbane Hydro-Electric Power Scheme |publisher=The Gazetteer for Scotland |accessdate=2 May 2014}}</ref>

Further facilities were added at [[Killin]] and [[Stronuich]].<ref name="CS80"/> The construction was completed in 1961. 

