[[File:1900 circa Arthur Weston glassine cover.jpg|thumb|Printed glassine envelope for the photographer [[Arthur Weston (photographer)|Arthur Weston]], about 1900]]
[[File:Pergamintüte.jpg|thumb|right|Glassine envelope]]
'''Glassine''' is a smooth and glossy [[paper]] that is air, water and grease resistant. It is usually available in densities between 50–90&nbsp;g/m<sup>2</sup>. It is [[translucent]] unless [[dye]]s are added to color it or make it [[Opacity (optics)|opaque]]. It is manufactured by [[calender|supercalendering]]: after pressing and drying, the paper web is passed through a stack of alternating steel and fiber-covered rolls called a supercalender at the end of the paper machine such that the paper fibres flatten facing in the same direction.
==Usage== Glassine is most commonly used as a base for further silicone coating for manufacture of [[release liner]]. Glassine is also employed as an interleaving paper in [[bookbinding]], especially to protect fine illustrations from contact with facing pages; the paper can be manufactured with a neutral [[pH]], and can prevent damage from spilling, exposure, or rubbing. Glassine [[adhesive tape]] has been used in book repair. In [[chemistry]], glassine is used as an inexpensive [[weighing paper]]. It is used in [[foodservice]] as a barrier between strips of products (for example: meat, [[baked goods]]). Glassine is resistant to [[Fat|grease]] and facilitates separation of individual foodstuffs.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}}
Glassine is also recommended for protecting the surface of stored acrylic paintings.<ref>[http://www.liquitex.com/acrylicbook/ The Acrylic book - A comprehensive resource for Artists] [[Copyright|©]] [[Liquitex]] Artist Materials 2007</ref> [[Philately|Philatelists]] use glassine [[envelope]]s to store stamps, and [[stamp hinge]]s are made of glassine.<ref>[http://linns.com/howto/refresher/mounts_20000320/refreshercourse.aspx Stamp hinges aren't perfect, but they do help<!-- Bot generated title -->] Michael Baadke</ref> Amateur insect collectors use glassine envelopes to store specimens temporarily in the field before they are mounted in a collection. Entomologists collecting for research may likewise use such envelopes to store whole specimens in the field. Glassine envelopes are used to carry pharmacy reformulated [[drug]]s and [[illicit drugs]] such as [[cocaine]] and [[heroin]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.usdoj.gov/dea/pubs/states/newsrel/nyc112806a.html | title = 60,000 Glassine Bags of Heroin Seized in Westchester | date = 2006-11-28 | publisher = DEA | quote = Law enforcement officers arrested Thevenin at that location and recovered two boxes containing approximately 60,000 individually packaged glassines of heroin. }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usdoj.gov/dea/pubs/states/newsrel/2008/nwk080408.html |title=DEA 'Brand' Used to Market Heroin |accessdate=2008-09-01 |date=2008-08-04 |publisher=DEA |quote=the DEA raided NUNEZs residence in the early hours of July 31, where heroin glassine bags (used to package heroin) were found that contained the official DEA Agency emblem. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822021744/http://www.usdoj.gov/dea/pubs/states/newsrel/2008/nwk080408.html |archivedate=2008-08-22 |df= }}</ref> In the mid-20th century, [[potato chip]]s were packaged in glassine bags.<ref>Burhans, Dirk E. (2008). ''Crunch: A History of the Great American Potato Chip'', p.33. Terrace Books, Madison Wi. {{ISBN|978-0-299-22770-8}}.</ref> Glassine is also used to pack [[firecracker]]s, as it is moisture resistant. It is used for its transparent qualities to fold [[origami]] [[tessellation]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spundreams.net/~andy/origami/tessellations.html|title=Andy's Tessellation Page|author=|date=|website=www.spundreams.net|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.origamitessellations.com/|title=Origami Tessellations|author=|date=|website=Origami Tessellations|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> Glassine is an outer covering on [[paperboard]] tubes, particularly those used in [[model rocketry]], for water protection.
